# React Component Conventions

## Function declarations, not arrow functions

```jsx
// ✅ GOOD
function MyComponent({ title, onAction }) { ... }

// ❌ BAD
const MyComponent = ({ title, onAction }) => { ... }
```

## Destructure props with defaults in the signature

```jsx
// ✅ GOOD
function Card({ id, title, isAuth = false, userId = null }) { ... }

// ❌ BAD
function Card(props) { const { id } = props; }
```

## Exports

- **Default export** for the main/page component of each file
- **Named export** for secondary helper components defined in the same file

```jsx
// ✅ GOOD — secondary component
function ErrorMessage({ msg }) { return <>{msg}</> }
export { ErrorMessage };

// ✅ GOOD — main component at the bottom
export default MyPage;
```

## Co-locate sub-components in the same file

Related presentational sub-components (e.g., a `Card`, `ListItem`, or inline error display) can live in the same file as the parent that uses them. Extract to a separate file only when reused across multiple files.

## Hooks to use

Use React and react-router hooks directly; do not wrap them unnecessarily:

- `useState`, `useEffect`, `useRef` — React core
- `useParams`, `useNavigate`, `useLocation`, `useOutletContext` — react-router
- `useRouteError` — in error boundary components

## Conditional rendering

Use ternary operators inline in JSX:

```jsx
// ✅ GOOD
{isAuth ? <LogoutButton /> : <LoginLink />}

// ✅ GOOD — short-circuit for optional elements
{isAuth && showEditor && <CommentEditor />}
```

## Functional components only

Never use class components.
